## 2. Relation family results

Per the user direction, four relation families were tested against E. The findings — all descriptive, none promotional — are:

### Relation 1: continuous monotone (linear-in-E fit on 10-bin half_phase_fraction)

| Fixture | slope | R² | Interpretation |
|---|---|---|---|
| `sr_four_form` | +0.065 | **0.143** | weak — relation family is likely not linear-in-E |
| `schwarzschild_four_form` | +0.067 | **0.474** | moderate — partial monotone trend; non-monotonic structure may dominate |
| `pure_algebraic_four_form` | +0.079 | **0.114** | weak — no clean monotone relation |

**Conclusion: linear-in-E is the wrong relation family** for two of three fixtures. Schwarzschild shows partial linearity (R² ~ 0.47), but SR and pure_algebraic do not.

### Relation 2: threshold (best single-cut on E maximizing half_phase contrast)

| Fixture | Best E threshold | frac_below | frac_above | abs contrast |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `sr_four_form` | −0.949 | 0.000 | 0.305 | **0.305** |
| `schwarzschild_four_form` | −0.750 | 0.009 | 0.682 | **0.673** |
| `pure_algebraic_four_form` | −0.752 | 0.000 | 0.357 | **0.357** |

**Conclusion: threshold is the dominant relation family.** All three fixtures show "below E ≈ −0.75 to −0.95, half_phase is essentially absent; above the threshold, it activates." This is consistent with a substrate-mandated lattice-granularity transition: when the radicand is small enough (E sufficiently negative), the half-phase signal is suppressed. The exact threshold values cluster around E ∈ [−0.95, −0.75], i.e., `|base_operand| ~ 0.5 to 0.6`, which is meaningful as it falls at the **Sterbenz/BACL boundary** of the natural function's domain.

### Relation 3: per-fixture residual after the linear-in-E model

After subtracting the linear fit, compute Pearson correlation of residuals with C-covariates:

| Fixture | corr(resid, J_condition) | corr(resid, hessian_abs) | corr(resid, endpoint_distance) | Max |corr| | Interpretation |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `sr_four_form` | +0.112 | +0.112 | −0.127 | 0.127 | weak — uncorrelated with C-covariates tested |
| `schwarzschild_four_form` | +0.181 | +0.179 | **+0.416** | 0.416 | **strong residual structure** — additional C-covariate dependence beyond E |
| `pure_algebraic_four_form` | +0.095 | +0.098 | +0.024 | 0.098 | weak |

**Conclusion: Schwarzschild has strong residual structure correlating with `endpoint_distance`** (the raw distance `|r − 2|`, not its log-image E). The linear-in-E model does not capture this. SR and pure_algebraic have weak residuals — the threshold model in Relation 2 fits them better than the linear model.

### Relation 4: transition grammar on the coordinate-sorted phase_class sequence

For each fixture, sort coordinates, take the phase_separation_class sequence, compute marginal entropy `H(X)`, conditional entropy `H(X_{t+1} | X_t)`, mutual information `MI = H(X) − H(X_{t+1} | X_t)`.

| Fixture | H_marginal (bits) | H_conditional (bits) | MI (bits) | MI / H_marginal ratio | Interpretation |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `sr_four_form` | 1.530 | 1.008 | **0.522** | **0.34** | strong transition structure |
| `schwarzschild_four_form` | 0.668 | 0.418 | **0.250** | **0.37** | strong transition structure |
| `pure_algebraic_four_form` | 1.180 | 0.313 | **0.867** | **0.74** | very strong transition structure |

**Conclusion: transition grammar carries strong structure across all three fixtures.** Consecutive phase classifications along the coordinate sweep are NOT independent given the marginal — there is substantial extra information in the *order* of phase classifications. The candidate G-curv-3 (transition grammar) is empirically validated as having structure, *but* whether that structure is reducible to E (i.e., C-driven via coordinate ordering correlating with E) or is a *second* independent primitive is **not yet known**. Resolving that is a separate Phase 2d-style follow-up.

